<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> The revision of the Nicene formula that this Council adopted may have been already used as the baptismal creed of Constantinople, as proposed by the Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church (Oxford University Press 2005, s.v. <i>Nicene Creed</i>).</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> The first record of the inclusion of this addition dates from the Third Council of Toledo in 589. Its use spread in the West, though <a href="/wiki/Pope_Leo_III" title="Pope Leo III">Pope Leo III</a> (795-816), who approved the doctrine, opposed its inclusion. The Creed, with the addition, was used in Rome itself for the first time only in 1014. See Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church (Oxford University Press 2005), article "Filioque".</li>
